      "content": "You're right, the MACRS formula for a 5-year asset is actually based on a declining balance method, where the asset's value decreases by a fixed percentage each year.\n\nFor a 5-year asset, the MACRS rates are:\n\nYear 1: 20%\nYear 2: 32%\nYear 3: 19.2%\nYear 4: 11.52%\nYear 5: 7.2%\n\nTo calculate the depreciation for each year, you multiply the asset's basis (initial cost) by the MACRS rate for that year.\n\nFor example, if the asset cost $100,000:\n\nYear 1: $100,000 x 20% = $20,000\nBasis: $100,000 - $20,000 = $80,000\n\nYear 2: $80,000 x 32% = $25,200\nBasis: $80,000 - $25,200 = $54,800\n\nYear 3: $54,800 x 19.2% = $10,449.60\nBasis: $54,800 - $10,449.60 = $44,350.40\n\nYear 4: $",
